<|startoftext|>Headline:"Trump's pick to head the U.S. Treasury, Steve Mnuchin, to stay in position,"Reuters reports: White House"
Content: "WASHINGTON/NEW YORK (Reuters) - U.S. President Donald Trump is set to nominate Steve Mnuchin to lead the Federal Reserve, the Federal Reserve Chair said on Sunday, the Washington Post reported on Sunday. A statement from Treasury Secretary Steve Mnuchin, quoted in the Post as saying he was making a decision on the nominee, said Mnuchin would remain in that job under Treasury Secretary Jacob Lew. In a memo to the National Economic Council, a White House committee staff member, Mnuchin said he had a “strong interest” in continuing to lead the FRC as he planned in his letter to Lew. “I would welcome the chance to move on from monetary policy to focus on creating jobs and strengthening our economy,” Mnuchin told Lew in a brief message. ",<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>Headline:Trump seeks to boost energy policy at meeting with Saudi king
Content: "WASHINGTON (Reuters) - U.S. President Donald Trump plans to push to boost the Department of Energy’s budget by $1.5 billion in next year, the energy industry source told Reuters, a week after a deal between OPEC and U.S. shale producers was scrapped. At a meeting between Trump and the Saudi King Salman on Sunday, President Donald Trump said he would press to cut the State Department’s budget by $300 million from 2018, according to the Energy Information and Financial Markets Administration of the Gulf Cooperation Council which negotiates energy deals between the four OPEC members. “This has allowed American workers and taxpayers to find jobs and to create jobs,” Trump said at the White House as he sat with his Energy Secretary Rick Perry. “This is a perfect example of American strength,” the White House said in a statement. “It is all too easy for foreign governments, especially Iran, to use our military and economic might to bully American businesses and companies.” ",<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>Headline:U.S. says it will move forward with new global climate agreement
Content: "WASHINGTON (Reuters) - The leaders of the U.S. and three other world powers met last weekend to hammer out a new global agreement to limit warming and tackle future conflicts, an ally said on Friday.  The next round of global efforts to curb climate change is not expected to be completed until next year, U.S. Secretary of State Rex Tillerson said in a Reuters interview. But Trump appeared to suggest it may take another six months. “Next year, we will do something like this to move the goalpost for the next phase, so that it is easier in five or six months to get out,” Tillerson said in an interview with Fox Business Network. Tillerson said the United States and China inked a memorandum of understanding last week outlining common standards and negotiating methods to make progress to limit global warming.  The United States has committed 100 percent to implementing a 2015 Paris Agreement to cut carbon dioxide from emissions in the period of negotiations beginning in the middle of 2018.  “That process is important - and it’s not just going to be solved by U.S. action or one that is going to go forward,” Tillerson told Fox Business Network, referring to negotiations.  China has said it will continue to reduce its emissions to meet the world’s goal of keeping temperature rise at no more than 2 degrees but is not signaling a strong determination to leave the agreement. Beijing also has said it might move ahead with a bigger emission reduction scheme to boost the share of coal in electricity output by 2018. “We’ll have to work with China to make sure that we have all the elements for the future we want to see in the world,” said Tillerson. ",<|endoftext|>
